prevalence increases with age (2.3% age Ͼ40 years; 5.9% age Ͼ65 years) and with the presence of structural heart disease such as ischemic, hypertensive, myocardial, or valvular disease. Lone AF typically occurs in young and middle-age adults (mean age at diagnosis ϳ44 years) (2). Although novel risk factors for this arrhythmia have recently been described (3–5), the etiology of an individual’s condition often remains unknown (6).
