Common AF Variants and Response to Antiarrhythmics

respective heterozygous variants. We used a similar analysis to test the association between AF recurrence within 12 months, as well as genetic polymorphism. Final dominant model for AF recurrence was adjusted for age, sex, AF type, history of hypertension, coronary artery disease, heart failure, diabetes, use of AADs, left ventricular ejection fraction, and left atrial size in the discovery cohort and age, sex, AF type, hypertension, and use of AADs in the validation cohort.
In the dominant model, an identical effect is expected in heterozygous and homozygous variant carriers, whereas in the additive model, heterozygous variant carriers have an intermediate effect in relation to the homozygotes. We used Bonferroni correction to correct for multiple testing with even distribution of signiﬁcance (alpha) among the 4 tested SNPs in the discovery cohort, with a 2-sided p value Ͻ0.0125 considered statistically signiﬁcant. For validation cohort (only 1 SNP tested), a 2-sided p value Ͻ0.05 was considered statistically signiﬁcant. All genetic analyses were performed with PLINK.
Results
Our study population consisted of 478 and 198 Caucasian patients enrolled in the discovery and validation cohorts, respectively. Clinical characteristics. The clinical characteristics of the study cohorts are summarized in Table 1. The discovery cohort consisted of 325 (68%) men, 152 (32%) women, age 63 Ϯ 13 years, 148 (31%) with lone AF, and hypertension was the most common underlying comorbidity in 207 (43%) patients. The validation cohort followed a similar trend: 129 (65%) men, 69 (35%) women, age 63 Ϯ 14 years, 53 (27%) with lone AF, and hypertension was found in 100 (50%) patients. Both study cohorts were similar with respect to baseline demographics except for larger left atrial size (46 Ϯ 8.6 mm) in the discovery cohort versus the validation cohort (44 Ϯ 9 mm), p ϭ 0.005, and a marginal difference in left

ventricular ejection fraction; 52 Ϯ 14% in the discovery cohort versus 53 Ϯ 11% in the validation cohort, p ϭ 0.05 in patients with typical AF. Genotyping. The frequencies of the common AF variants between responders and nonresponders did not deviate signiﬁcantly from Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium. Table 2 shows the genotype frequencies of the tested SNPs in both study cohorts. Response to AAD therapy. In the discovery cohort, 399 (83.5%) patients met the criteria of successful rhythm control. Response to therapy (successful rhythm control) was signiﬁcantly associated with rs10033464 in patients with typical AF; allelic chi-square ϭ 0.0026, genotypic chi-square ϭ 0.0008. There was marginal genotypic association of the same SNP in the cumulative discovery cohort (typical and lone AF); chi-square ϭ 0.03.
Multiple clinical variables (including age, hypertension, lone AF) failed to signiﬁcantly predict response to AADs. By contrast, rs10033464 at 4q25 in regression analysis under both the dominant and additive models was signiﬁcantly associated with successful rhythm control in patients with typical AF carrying the ancestral allele (wild type) versus carriers of variant allele (odds ratio [OR]: 4.59, 95% conﬁdence interval [CI]: 1.82 to 11.5, p ϭ 0.0012 and OR: 3.03, 95% CI: 1.41 to 6.50, p ϭ 0.004, respectively). This association persisted after correction for multiple clinical factors (OR: 4.70, 95% CI: 1.83 to 12.0, p ϭ 0.0013 and OR: 3.44, 95% CI: 1.52 to 7.76, p ϭ 0.003, respectively) (Table 3).
There was a differential response to the class of AADs in variants of rs10033464. Wild types responded better to class III AADs, p ϭ 0.02, whereas carriers of variant allele responded better to class I AADs, p ϭ 0.02 (Table 4).
In the validation cohort, 143 (72%) patients met the criteria for rhythm control. Response to therapy was again signiﬁcantly associated with rs10033464; chi-square ϭ 0.042. In similar genetic regression models as the discovery

